issues.title: Infotainment System Freezing and Rebooting
issues.description: The Mercedes-based COMAND infotainment system frequently freezes, crashes, or randomly reboots during operation, causing loss of navigation, audio, and climate control functionality.
issues.fix_description: Software update or complete infotainment unit replacement
issues.prevention: Avoid using multiple functions simultaneously and keep software updated

issues.title: Turbocharger Failure
issues.description: Twin turbochargers on V8 models suffer from premature failure, particularly the turbine wheels and wastegate actuators, leading to significant power loss and potential engine damage.
issues.fix_description: Complete turbocharger replacement with updated components
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, proper warm-up procedures, and avoid excessive idling

issues.title: Battery Drain Issues
issues.description: Excessive battery drain when parked, often caused by electronic modules failing to enter sleep mode properly, leading to dead batteries and starting issues.
issues.fix_description: Software updates to affected modules or replacement of faulty control units
issues.prevention: Regular driving and using a battery tender for extended storage

issues.title: Air Suspension Compressor Failure
issues.description: Air suspension compressor fails prematurely, causing the vehicle to sag or ride at incorrect height, particularly affecting rear suspension components.
issues.fix_description: Replace air suspension compressor and check air lines for leaks
issues.prevention: Regular inspection of air suspension components and avoid overloading

issues.title: Door Handle Mechanism Failure
issues.description: Electronic door handles fail to operate properly, with handles either not extending when approached or retracting while being used, trapping occupants.
issues.fix_description: Replace door handle mechanism and update software calibration
issues.prevention: Gentle operation and regular lubrication of mechanical components

issues.title: Engine Oil Consumption
issues.description: Excessive engine oil consumption on both V8 and V12 engines, often requiring oil top-ups between services and potentially leading to engine damage if unmonitored.
issues.fix_description: Engine rebuild or replacement depending on severity of wear
issues.prevention: Regular oil level monitoring and premium oil usage

issues.title: Carbon Fiber Body Panel Delamination
issues.description: Carbon fiber body panels, particularly on the AMR variants, experience delamination or separation of carbon fiber layers, affecting structural integrity and aesthetics.
issues.prevention: Avoid extreme temperature changes and physical impacts

issues.title: Brake System Premature Wear
issues.description: Carbon ceramic brakes experience premature wear and warping, leading to reduced braking performance and expensive replacement costs much earlier than expected.
issues.fix_description: Complete brake disc and pad replacement with updated specifications
issues.prevention: Proper brake warm-up procedures and avoiding extreme temperature cycling

issues.title: Transmission Control Module Failure
issues.description: ZF 8-speed automatic transmission control module fails, causing erratic shifting, transmission slipping, and potentially complete transmission failure.
issues.fix_description: Replace transmission control module and reprogram transmission software
issues.prevention: Regular transmission fluid changes and avoiding aggressive driving patterns

issues.title: Cooling System Leaks
issues.description: Multiple cooling system components including radiators, hoses, and water pumps develop leaks, potentially leading to engine overheating and catastrophic damage.
issues.fix_description: Replace faulty cooling system components and pressure test entire system
issues.prevention: Regular coolant changes and inspection of hoses and connections

editorial.tagline: British grand touring perfection meets modern performance
editorial.hero_blurb: The DB11 represents Aston Martin's triumphant return to form, blending timeless British elegance with cutting-edge technology. Whether powered by the thunderous V12 or the more efficient twin-turbo V8, this grand tourer delivers an intoxicating mix of luxury and performance that few can match.
editorial.essence: The DB11 is the quintessential modern grand tourer, offering a perfect balance of everyday usability and weekend thrills. It's a car that can cross continents in supreme comfort while still delivering heart-pounding performance when the mood strikes.
editorial.heritage: Following in the footsteps of the legendary DB series that began in the 1940s, the DB11 carries forward Aston Martin's tradition of elegant, high-performance grand tourers. Named after company founder David Brown, the DB lineage includes icons like the DB5 and DB9, with the DB11 representing the latest evolution of this storied bloodline.
editorial.design_philosophy: Marek Reichman's design team crafted a shape that honors Aston Martin's heritage while pushing boldly into the future, featuring flowing lines, the signature grille, and innovative aerodynamics including the distinctive roof strakes that channel air through the rear fenders.
editorial.motorsport_history: While the DB11 itself isn't a race car, it benefits from Aston Martin's extensive motorsport heritage, including Le Mans victories and Formula 1 participation, with racing-derived technologies filtered down to enhance road car performance and handling.
editorial.engine_character: The 5.2L V12 delivers brutal, linear power with old-school character, while the 4.0L V8 (sourced from AMG) provides more immediate turbo thrust with impressive efficiency, both engines offering distinctly different but equally compelling personalities.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 8-speed automatic gearbox shifts smoothly in comfort mode and crisply in sport settings, though it occasionally hesitates during aggressive driving, preferring the grand touring rhythm over track-day urgency.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: The adaptive suspension strikes an excellent balance between comfort and control, with three-stage dampers that can transform the car from a plush cruiser to a focused sports car at the touch of a button.
editorial.steering_feel: The electric power steering offers good weight and precision, though it lacks the ultimate connection of hydraulic systems, providing adequate feedback for spirited driving while remaining effortless during long-distance cruising.
editorial.brake_confidence: The carbon-ceramic brakes (when optioned) provide tremendous stopping power with excellent fade resistance, though the initial bite can feel grabby in everyday driving, requiring some adaptation to modulate smoothly.
editorial.sound_signature: The V12 produces a cultured, aristocratic growl that builds to a glorious wail at high revs, while the V8 offers a more aggressive, crackling soundtrack with distinctive pops and burbles on overrun.
editorial.ideal_owner: The DB11 is perfect for the sophisticated enthusiast who values style as much as performance, someone who appreciates British craftsmanship and wants a car that can handle both business meetings and weekend getaways with equal aplomb.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Track-focused drivers seeking ultimate lap times, budget-conscious buyers concerned about maintenance costs, or those who prioritize rear seat space and practicality over style and performance.
editorial.buyers_summary: Choose the V12 for maximum drama and exclusivity, or the V8 for better balance and efficiency. Both offer stunning looks and genuine grand touring capability, though be prepared for Aston Martin's typical quirks and premium maintenance costs.
